The sequence formula_50 is said to be locally uniformly convergent with limit formula_2 if formula_88 is a metric space and for every formula_21, there exists an formula_90 such that formula_1 converges uniformly on formula_92 It is clear that uniform convergence implies local uniform convergence, which implies pointwise convergence.

=== Notes ===

Intuitively, a sequence of functions formula_11 converges uniformly to formula_2 if, given an arbitrarily small formula_95, we can find an formula_96 so that the functions formula_11 with formula_98 all fall within a &quot;tube&quot; of width formula_99 centered around formula_2 (i.e., between formula_101 and formula_102) for the &quot;entire domain&quot; of the function.

Note that interchanging the order of quantifiers in the definition of uniform convergence by moving &quot;for all formula_21&quot; in front of &quot;there exists a natural number formula_5&quot; results in a definition of pointwise convergence of the sequence. To make this difference explicit, in the case of uniform convergence, formula_22 can only depend on formula_4, and the choice of formula_5 has to work for all formula_21, for a specific value of formula_4 that is given. In contrast, in the case of pointwise convergence, formula_110 may depend on both formula_4 and formula_9, and the choice of formula_5 only has to work for the specific values of formula_4 and formula_9 that are given. Thus uniform convergence implies pointwise convergence, however the converse is not true, as the example in the section below illustrates.

=== Generalizations ===

One may straightforwardly extend the concept to functions &quot;E&quot; → &quot;M&quot;, where (&quot;M&quot;, &quot;d&quot;) is a metric space, by replacing formula_116 with formula_117.

The most general setting is the uniform convergence of nets of functions &quot;E&quot; → &quot;X&quot;, where &quot;X&quot; is a uniform space. We say that the net formula_118 &quot;converges uniformly&quot; with limit &quot;f&quot; : &quot;E&quot; → &quot;X&quot; if and only if for every entourage &quot;V&quot; in &quot;X&quot;, there exists an formula_119, such that for every &quot;x&quot; in &quot;E&quot; and every formula_120, formula_121 is in &quot;V&quot;. In this situation, uniform limit of continuous functions remains continuous.

===Definition in a hyperreal setting===
Uniform convergence admits a simplified definition in a hyperreal setting. Thus, a sequence formula_11 converges to &quot;f&quot; uniformly if for all hyperreal &quot;x&quot; in the domain of formula_123 and all infinite &quot;n&quot;, formula_124 is infinitely close to formula_125 (see microcontinuity for a similar definition of uniform continuity). In contrast, pointwise continuity requires this only for real &quot;x&quot;.

