and take formula_211

If formula_212 is convergent, then the M-test asserts that the original series is uniformly convergent.

The ratio test can be used here:

:formula_213

which means the series over formula_207 is convergent. Thus the original series converges uniformly for all formula_215 and since formula_216, the series is also uniformly convergent on formula_217

== Properties ==

* Every uniformly convergent sequence is locally uniformly convergent.
* Every locally uniformly convergent sequence is compactly convergent.
* For locally compact spaces local uniform convergence and compact convergence coincide.
* A sequence of continuous functions on metric spaces, with the image metric space being complete, is uniformly convergent if and only if it is uniformly Cauchy.
* If formula_218 is a compact interval (or in general a compact topological space), and formula_219 is a monotone increasing sequence (meaning formula_220 for all &quot;n&quot; and &quot;x&quot;) of &quot;continuous&quot; functions with a pointwise limit formula_221 which is also continuous, then the convergence is necessarily uniform (Dini&#x27;s theorem). Uniform convergence is also guaranteed if formula_222 is a compact interval and formula_1 is an equicontinuous sequence that converges pointwise.

== Applications ==

===To continuity===

If formula_3 and formula_225 are topological spaces, then it makes sense to talk about the continuity of the functions formula_226. If we further assume that formula_225 is a metric space, then (uniform) convergence of the formula_11 to formula_2 is also well defined. The following result states that continuity is preserved by uniform convergence:

This theorem is proved by the &quot; trick&quot;, and is the archetypal example of this trick: to prove a given inequality (), one uses the definitions of continuity and uniform convergence to produce 3 inequalities (), and then combines them via the triangle inequality to produce the desired inequality.

This theorem is an important one in the history of real and Fourier analysis, since many 18th century mathematicians had the intuitive understanding that a sequence of continuous functions always converges to a continuous function. The image above shows a counterexample, and many discontinuous functions could, in fact, be written as a Fourier series of continuous functions. The erroneous claim that the pointwise limit of a sequence of continuous functions is continuous (originally stated in terms of convergent series of continuous functions) is infamously known as &quot;Cauchy&#x27;s wrong theorem&quot;. The uniform limit theorem shows that a stronger form of convergence, uniform convergence, is needed to ensure the preservation of continuity in the limit function.

More precisely, this theorem states that the uniform limit of &quot;uniformly continuous&quot; functions is uniformly continuous; for a locally compact space, continuity is equivalent to local uniform continuity, and thus the uniform limit of continuous functions is continuous.
===To differentiability===
If formula_218 is an interval and all the functions formula_11 are differentiable and converge to a limit formula_2, it is often desirable to determine the derivative function formula_233 by taking the limit of the sequence formula_234. This is however in general not possible: even if the convergence is uniform, the limit function need not be differentiable (not even if the sequence consists of everywhere-analytic functions, see Weierstrass function), and even if it is differentiable, the derivative of the limit function need not be equal to the limit of the derivatives. Consider for instance formula_235 with uniform limit formula_236. Clearly, formula_233 is also identically zero. However, the derivatives of the sequence of functions are given by formula_238 and the sequence formula_234 does not converge to formula_240 or even to any function at all. In order to ensure a connection between the limit of a sequence of differentiable functions and the limit of the sequence of derivatives, the uniform convergence of the sequence of derivatives plus the convergence of the sequence of functions at at least one point is required:

: &quot;If formula_1 is a sequence of differentiable functions on formula_242 such that formula_243 exists (and is finite) for some formula_244 and the sequence formula_245 converges uniformly on formula_242, then formula_11 converges uniformly to a function formula_2 on formula_242, and formula_250 for formula_251.&quot;

===To integrability===
Similarly, one often wants to exchange integrals and limit processes. For the Riemann integral, this can be done if uniform convergence is assumed:
: &quot;If formula_252 is a sequence of Riemann integrable functions defined on a compact interval formula_253 which uniformly converge with limit formula_221, then formula_221 is Riemann integrable and its integral can be computed as the limit of the integrals of the formula_256:&quot; formula_257
In fact, for a uniformly convergent family of bounded functions on an interval, the upper and lower Riemann integrals converge to the upper and lower Riemann integrals of the limit function. This follows because, for &quot;n&quot; sufficiently large, the graph of formula_11 is within of the graph of &quot;f&quot;, and so the upper sum and lower sum of formula_11 are each within formula_260 of the value of the upper and lower sums of formula_2, respectively.

Much stronger theorems in this respect, which require not much more than pointwise convergence, can be obtained if one abandons the Riemann integral and uses the Lebesgue integral instead.

===To analyticity===
Using Morera&#x27;s Theorem, one can show that if a sequence of analytic functions converges uniformly in a region S of the complex plane, then the limit is analytic in S. This example demonstrates that complex functions are more well-behaved than real functions, since the uniform limit of analytic functions on a real interval need not even be differentiable (see Weierstrass function).

===To series===
We say that formula_262 converges:

With this definition comes the following result:
Let &quot;x&quot;0 be contained in the set &quot;E&quot; and each &quot;f&quot;&quot;n&quot; be continuous at &quot;x&quot;0. If formula_263 converges uniformly on &quot;E&quot; then &quot;f&quot; is continuous at &quot;x&quot;0 in &quot;E&quot;. Suppose that formula_264 and each &quot;f&quot;&quot;n&quot; is integrable on &quot;E&quot;. If formula_262 converges uniformly on &quot;E&quot; then &quot;f&quot; is integrable on &quot;E&quot; and the series of integrals of &quot;f&quot;&quot;n&quot; is equal to integral of the series of fn.

==Almost uniform convergence==
If the domain of the functions is a measure space &quot;E&quot; then the related notion of almost uniform convergence can be defined. We say a sequence of functions formula_1 converges almost uniformly on &quot;E&quot; if for every formula_267 there exists a measurable set formula_268 with measure less than formula_269 such that the sequence of functions formula_1 converges uniformly on formula_271. In other words, almost uniform convergence means there are sets of arbitrarily small measure for which the sequence of functions converges uniformly on their complement.

Note that almost uniform convergence of a sequence does not mean that the sequence converges uniformly almost everywhere as might be inferred from the name. However, Egorov&#x27;s theorem does guarantee that on a finite measure space, a sequence of functions that converges almost everywhere also converges almost uniformly on the same set.

Almost uniform convergence implies almost everywhere convergence and convergence in measure.

